model_lasso <- cv.glmnet(x, y, family = "binomial", alpha = 1)

The colnames() function is used to get the names of all variables, and the non-zero coefficient names are extracted and sorted in order of importance.

model <- glmnet(x, y, family = "binomial", alpha = 1, lambda = lambda.min)



# The model.matrix() function is used to create the design matrix for the training dataset, and the predict() function is used to generate the probability of default for each customer in the training dataset
# Predict on training set
#The loss for each customer is calculated by multiplying the probability of default by the loan amount. The MAE is then calculated by taking the absolute difference between the loss and the true loss (which is the loan amount if there is no default, or 0 if there is a default), and then taking the mean of these absolute differences.

prob <- predict(model, newx = x, type = "response")
loss <- prob * loan_train_final$amount
MAE <- mean(abs(loss - ifelse(loan_train_final$default == 0, 0, loan_train_final$amount)))

#In this question, the Lasso regression model has been chosen to predict default probabilities because it allows us to select only the most important variables and avoid overfitting. By doing so, the model can be more robust and generalize better to new data.
#To ensure that the Lasso model is not overfitting the training data, cross-validation (CV) is used to select the optimal value of the regularization parameter, lambda. This is done by splitting the data into training and validation sets and repeatedly fitting the model on different subsets of the training data. The optimal lambda value is the one that results in the lowest cross-validation error.
#By selecting the optimal lambda value, we can be confident that the Lasso model is not overfitting to the training data. Furthermore, we can use the selected variables to build a simpler and more interpretable model. This is because the Lasso regression model selects only the most important variables and sets the coefficients of less important variables to zero.

#Write a function pca-recover that returns the slope of the first component of the PCA 
pca_recover <- function(X, Y) {
  # center the data
  X_centered <- X - mean(X)
  Y_centered <- Y - mean(Y)
  
  # create the data matrix
  data_matrix <- cbind(X_centered, Y_centered)
  
  # calculate the covariance matrix
  cov_matrix <- cov(data_matrix)
  length(cov_matrix)
  
  # calculate the eigenvectors and eigenvalues
  eig_vals <- eigen(cov_matrix)$values
  eig_vecs <- eigen(cov_matrix)$vectors
    
#Since largest eigenvalue corresponds to the most important eigenvector i.e the first principal component vector whose slope we need to find for this question
#In this specific case, we have two variables X and Y, and we want to find the slope of the line that best describes their relationship. We can do this by finding the first principal component of the data, which corresponds to the direction in which the data varies the most. The slope of this line (or direction) is simply the coefficient that relates the two variables along this direction.
#So, finding the slope of the first principal component means finding the coefficient that best describes the linear relationship between X and Y along the direction of greatest variability in the data.
  index <- which.max(eig_vals)
  
 #The slope of a line is defined as the change in y divided by the change in x
#In the context of PCA, the first principal component represents the direction of maximum variation in the data. Let's say that the first principal component has an eigenvector v = [v1, v2]. This means that if we move one unit along the direction of the first principal component (which corresponds to v), the y-coordinate changes by v2, and the x-coordinate changes by v1.

 #compute slope of first principal component

  slope <- eig_vecs[2, index] / eig_vecs[1, index]
  
  return(slope)
}


#part1- b
#Write a function ls-recover that takes X and Y and returns theslope of the least squares fit
ls_recover <- function(X, Y) {
  model <- lm(Y ~ X)  # fitting a linear regression model
  coef(model)[2]  # returns the slope (coefficient of X)
}

# Set X and Y
X <- seq(0.001, 1, by = 0.001)

#part 2-  Assume that X and Y are IID (independent and identically distributed) random variables that are generated randomly within the square [0, 1] × [0, 1]. The goal is to understand how the PCA and LS methods behave in this scenario, where there is no predetermined linear relationship between X and Y.

#If X and Y were chosen identically and independently at random in the square [0, 1] × [0, 1], the true relationship between X and Y is not deterministic but a random function.
#Under the assumption that X and Y are independent and identically distributed, the variance of X and the variance of Y should be equal. This is because the variance of a random variable is a measure of how spread out its values are, and since X and Y have the same probability distribution, they will have the same spread or variability.
#Var(X) = E[(X - E[X])^2] = E[(X - E[Y])^2] = Var(Y)
#Therefore, the direction of greatest variance in the data will be equally aligned with the x-axis and y-axis, since both variables have the same spread of values along each axis. As a result, the first principal component of the data will be equally aligned with the x-axis and y-axis, and will have a slope of 0. This means that the PCA algorithm will not be able to recover any meaningful relationship between X and Y, since the first principal component corresponds to a direction that is equally aligned with both variables.


v1 <- c()
v2 <- c()
set.seed(5765)
for (i in 1:1000){
  X1 <- runif(n=1000, 0, 1)
  Y1 <- runif(n=1000, 0, 1)
  v1[i] <- pca_recover(X1,Y1)
  v2[i] <- ls_recover(X1,Y1)
}
plot(v1) #plot shows slope =0 from pca_recover

mean(v2) #mean of slopes obtained from ls_recover is 0
## [1] 0.0008202791
#Similarly, for LS, we would obtain the best-fit line between X and Y, but since X and Y are independent and identically distributed, there is no underlying linear relationship that can be captured by the least squares regression. The slope of the least squares fit would also be close to zero, indicating no significant linear relationship between X and Y.
#Therefore, in this case, neither PCA nor LS would be able to recover the true linear relationship between X and Y, as there is no such relationship present in the data.

library(ggplot2)
# Define X and the noise levels
X <- seq(0.001, 1, by = 0.001)

c_values <- seq(0, 0.5, by = 0.05)

# Sample Y_hat, compute PCA recover and LS recover, and store the results in a data frame
set.seed(123) # Set seed for reproducibility
results <- data.frame(c = numeric(length(c_values)), pca = numeric(length(c_values)), ls = numeric(length(c_values)))
for (i in seq_along(c_values)) {
  for (j in 1:30) {
    y_hat <- 2 * X + rnorm(length(X), 0, c_values[i])
    pca_rec <- pca_recover(X, y_hat)
    ls_rec <- ls_recover(X, y_hat)
    results <- rbind(results, data.frame(c = c_values[i], pca = pca_rec, ls = ls_rec))
  }
}

#part5- In which case does PCA do better ? Why ? 

#PCA performs better in the second case(in part4) which is the case where our data consists of noisy estimates of both x and y. We can clearly see from the plot that when both x and y are noisy, slope from first principal component is more accurate i.e close to 2. On the other hand, least squares perform better when there is noise only in y variable & x is fixed noisefree.

#Reasoning: 

#Fixed X values or X values independent of the error term is one of the main assumptions of classical linear regression model.It is assumed that X variables and the error term are independent, that is, cov(Xi,ui)=0 i.e independent variables are not related with errors. These assumptions, in turn, imply that the errors are in the dependent variable (y) and not in the independent variable (x). The error term represents the variability or noise in the model that cannot be explained by the independent variable. This is because, in the linear regression model, the dependent variable is modeled as a function of the independent variable(s) and the errors, and therefore any noise or error in the model must be in the dependent variable. While this assumption is not explicitly stated as one of the classical assumptions of linear regression, it is often implicitly assumed or inferred from the other assumptions.
##In the first scenario, if we use the least squares method to estimate the linear relationship between x and y, we might still obtain reliable results, because the noise in y is independent of x and does not affect the true relationship between them significantly. However, in the second scenario, the least squares method might not perform as well, because the noise in both x and y can introduce more variability and confound the true relationship between them.
#In the second scenario where both x and y are noisy, PCA can perform better than least squares regression.
#The reason for this is that PCA is a method that can reduce the dimensionality of the data while preserving the most important information. In other words, PCA can identify the principal components that explain the maximum variance in the data, and reduce the dimensions of the data to these components.
#When there is noise in the data, the principal components can help filter out the noise and capture the underlying structure of the data more effectively. This is because the principal components represent the directions of maximum variation in the data, and noise typically contributes less to this variation compared to the signal.

#Question 4 Causal inference

#part1 - a 

#Y(0) represents the potential outcome for an individual if they do not receive treatment (placebo), while Y(1) represents the potential outcome for the same individual if they do receive treatment.

#part1- b

#The causal effect of receiving treatment for the first unit can be calculated as the difference between Y(1) and Y(0) for that unit. Therefore, for the first unit, the causal effect of receiving treatment is 95 - 80 = 15.

#part1 - c

#The average treatment effect in this population can be calculated as the difference between the average potential outcome under treatment (Y(1)) and the average potential outcome under no treatment (Y(0)). Therefore, the average treatment effect in this population is:
#[(95 + 70) / 2] - [(82 + 70 + 60) / 3] = 11.83
Average_y1 = (95+70)/2
Average_y0 = (70+60+82)/3
Averae_treatmenteffect =Average_y1-Average_y0 #11.83

#part1 -d

#In a randomized study, T is independent of Y(0) and T is independent of Y(1) because the treatment assignment is random and does not depend on the potential outcomes.In other words, assignment to treatment should be uncorrelated with the outcome. This requirement is automatically satisfied if T is assigned randomly, since then T and the outcomes are independent. If this requirement is satisfied, there will be no selection bias.
#In a randomized study, the treatment assignment T is assumed to be independent of any other factors that might influence the potential outcomes Y (0) and Y (1). This means that the treatment assignment is determined purely by chance and not influenced by any factors that might be related to the potential outcomes. Therefore, T is independent of Y (0) and T is independent of Y (1).

#However, T is not independent of Y(obs), which represents the observed outcome for an individual.
#Once the treatment has been assigned and the potential outcomes have been realized, the observed outcome Yobs is no longer independent of the treatment assignment T. This is because the treatment assignment T affects the observed outcome Y(obs), and thus the two variables are no longer independent. In other words, the observed outcome is a function of both the treatment assignment and the potential outcomes, and therefore Y obs is not independent of T.

#part2 b

#When we say that the treatment groups are unconfounded on X, we mean that the assignment of individuals to the treatment or control group is independent of their potential outcomes, conditional on their observed values of X. This means that the distributions of X in the treatment and control groups are balanced, so that any differences in the outcome variable between the two groups can be attributed to the treatment effect rather than confounding by X. To summarize, unconfoundedness on X means that the distribution of X is balanced between the treatment and control groups, so that any differences in the outcome variable can be attributed to the treatment effect.

# we can express the unconfoundedness assumption as follows:
#(Y1, Y0) ⊥ T | X
#This assumption is important because it allows us to estimate the causal effect of the treatment on the outcome variable Y by comparing the mean outcome in the treatment group to the mean outcome in the control group, under the assumption that any differences between these means are solely due to the treatment and not to confounding factors.

#part2 c

#The treatment assignment is not unconfounded for the value of X because there are imbalances in the number of individuals in the treatment and control groups for X=1. Specifically, there are more individuals with X=1 in the treatment group(75 people) than in the control group(25 people), which may lead to confounding by X.
#If the treatment assignment is not unconfounded given X, then the comparison of Yobs between the treatment and control groups may not be a valid estimate of the treatment effect, as differences in the outcomes may be due to differences in the distribution of covariates (X) rather than the treatment itself.

#part 2 d

#The propensity score is the probability of receiving treatment given a person's observed characteristics. It is used to control for confounding due to observed covariates in causal inference.
#The propensity score p(X) is defined as the conditional probability of receiving the treatment T=1 given a set of observed covariates X. In other words, it is the probability of being in the treatment group given a person's observed characteristics. By estimating the propensity score, one can balance the distribution of observed covariates between the treatment and control groups by matching. 
#the propensity score can be written as:
#p(X) = P(T=1|X)

#Total no of individuals treatment - 125

#we will match 125 people in treatment with the 75 people in treatment based on the propensity scores. Matching will need to be done with replacement and ultimately we will have 125 pairs. In this we just have one X as a confounder variable which is binary variable. So we can do 'EXACT MATCHING ' in control and treatment based on the value of X.

#Out of the 125 people assigned to treatment, 75 have X = 1 and 50 have X = 0. Therefore, the probability of treatment assignment when X = 1 is 75/125 = 0.6, and the probability of treatment assignment when X = 0 is 50/125 = 0.4.

#The plan to first use Lasso regression to select predictors with nonzero coefficients and then use these predictors in a random forest model is a reasonable idea, and it can be an effective way to reduce the number of features to a manageable level while still retaining most of the predictive power. By shrinking some of the coefficients to zero, Lasso can create a more parsimonious model and avoid overfitting. Furthermore, the use of cross-validation ensures that the model is not overfitting the training data. Using a reduced set of predictors from the Lasso model can make the random forest model more computationally efficient without sacrificing much predictive power. However, it's important to note that the Lasso model may not identify all the important predictors, and some relevant predictors may have been eliminated due to the penalty on the coefficients. Therefore, it's important to carefully examine the selected predictors and consider other methods for variable selection to ensure that the most relevant predictors are included in the final model.

One possible reason for this overfitting is that the model is too complex relative to the size of the training data. With only 1200 observations and 37 predictors, the lasso model may be struggling to identify the most important predictors while avoiding overfitting.

It is important to strike a balance between model complexity and the number of predictors to avoid overfitting.Another possible solution is to gather more data to increase the sample size, which can help the model generalize better to new data. If some predictors are not relevant for the test set, they may be removed from the model to improve its generalization performance.
